# Code Chunk 1: Load Data

```{r}
# Load built-in dataset
data(mtcars)

# View first few rows
head(mtcars)
```

# Code Chunk 2: Summary Statistics

```{r}
# Summary statistics
summary(mtcars)
```

# Code Chunk 3: Simple Plot

```{r}
# Basic scatter plot
plot(mtcars$wt, mtcars$mpg,
     main = "Car Weight vs MPG",
     xlab = "Weight",
     ylab = "Miles Per Gallon")
```

# Conclusion / Reflection

Using R Markdown was a different experience compared to writing a traditional report. Instead of separating code and writing, everything is integrated into one workflow. This makes the process more efficient and reduces the risk of inconsistencies between reported results and actual outputs.

One challenge was learning the syntax for Markdown and remembering how to properly format code chunks. Additionally, ensuring that the document “knits” correctly required some troubleshooting. However, once everything worked, the final output was clean, organized, and professional. Overall, R Markdown is a valuable tool for reproducible research and data analysis.
